		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2010"></a><br><code>sle2010/keynote1</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2010</a> keynote:</span><br><i>A Language for Software Variation Research</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/MartinErwig.html">Martin Erwig</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-19440-5_1">10.1007/978-3-642-19440-5_1</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2c.html"><span class="tagM">T2C: Variability</span></a><ul><li> The talk proposes a calculus for representing and reasoning about software variation (features, configurations, versions) as a unifying variability model.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1c.html"><span class="tagL">T1C: Behavioural Semantics</span></a><ul><li> It sketches the semantics of the choice calculus and how variation is eliminated via dimension/tag selection.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> The choice calculus is presented as a domain-focused language for variation research and applications such as feature modeling.
</li></ul></li></ul>
